ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic activity of the prepared materials was evaluated for EfOM removal at a fixed dose of 0.4 g•L−1. In addition to evaluating the DOC removal percentage, the pseudo-first-order kinetic constants were calculated for the photocatalytic degradation of EfOM (R2 = 0.86–0.96). DOC removal was negligible for the control samples in the absence of the photocatalyst (Fig. 4
                           ). The preliminary results revealed that adsorption–desorption equilibria between the EfOM and photocatalysts could be achieved in 1 h (Fig. S2), and a higher adsorption tendency was observed for nsC3N4 compared to that of Bi2WO6 (Table S2). These results are consistent with those of a previous study that reported preferential DOM adsorption onto carbonaceous π-conjugated materials (e.g., nsC3N4 
                           [8], biochar [9], and graphene oxide [53]) via π-π interactions with aromatic structures in DOM. In this study, Bi2WO6 exhibited better EfOM degradation than nsC3N4 (11.6 ± 0.5% and 6.8 ± 0.7%, respectively), likely due to the ability of Bi2WO6 to generate strong OH active species [49]. For the binary composites, the combination of nsC3N4 and Bi2WO6 exhibited enhanced DOC removal in the range of 21.5–34.2% compared to those of the single-component materials. Among the binary composites, CB40 exhibited the highest photocatalytic activity with a total DOC removal of 34.2 ± 0.9% and a degradation rate constant of 0.045 h−1. The improved performance is attributed to the nsC3N4 loading on the surface of the Bi2WO6 microspheres, which extends the light adsorption edge of the composite as well as the interfacial contact of the two hosts, promoting e−–h+ pair separation. These justifications are supported by the lower PL emission intensity of CB40 compared to those of the hosts (Fig. 1e). The lower DOC removal efficiencies of CB60 and CB80 compared to that of CB40 may be attributed to the abundant nsC3N4 surrounding the Bi2WO6 surface and its ability to hinder visible light absorption.
